snippet.textDisplay:
Utter rubbish. In Australia bushfire fighting funding and resource management is and always has been the sole responsibility of individual State and Local Governments to provide and arrange according with State Legislation and time-proven best practice predicated upon the need to cater resources and funding to individual regional needs and climatic conditions. Commonwealth Government assistance is only able to be provided at the specific direct request of those very same State and Local Government leaders who both demand to be in sole control of resourcing and budgetary provision of bushfire fighting resources and therefore are themselves solely responsible for the inadequate preparation for and mishandling of the current circumstances.



Expecting the Prime Minister to be able to simply 'stop' the situation of a natural disaster when inadequate preventative measures have been undertaken by stupid State politicians is akin to blaming someone for the conducts of their brothers and sisters. If the Commonwealth Government had attempted to intervene in the manner these people and others now apparently (and notably only retrospectively) expect, those very same people would have been screaming about this being inappropriate interference from Canberra.

Living within an area of extreme fire danger myself, it's most clear that the incremental creep over the last decade of Local and State Government bans upon the burning of fuel loads which now even forbid doing this during Winter, in priority of maintaining 'tourist amenity', have more to do with the intensity of this natural disaster than any action much less inaction on behalf of the Prime Minister.
